        "children": [
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-4125284bf132403bb6d3d24ddaf2552d",
            "meta": {
              "previousId": "builder-352a6a2ee7884de89bfa0f2d371716b1"
            },
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<p>Making the move from EVM to SVM (Solana) requires understanding several key differences between the virtual machines. This article will walk through several of those differences, including accounts, fees, transactions, smart contracts (programs), and more. It will also explore developer setup including tooling and SDKs.&nbsp;</p><p>By the end, developers will have the knowledge needed to start their Solana journey.</p>"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-352a6a2ee7884de89bfa0f2d371716b1",
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<h2>Understanding the Core Differences&nbsp;</h2><p>To start, let’s look at the most significant difference between EVM and SVM—the account model design.</p><h3>Account Model</h3><p>Unlike Ethereum, Solana was designed to take advantage of multiple cores and support parallel <a href=\"https://solana.com/docs/core/transactions\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">transactions</a>. To achieve this, Solana uses an account model.</p><p>An <a href=\"https://solana.com/developers/evm-to-svm/accounts\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">account</a> on Solana is a record in the Solana ledger that either holds data (a data account) or is an executable program (a smart contract or <a href=\"https://solana.com/developers/evm-to-svm/smart-contracts\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><em>program</em></a> on Solana).&nbsp;</p><p>Like Ethereum, each account has an address identifier. However, unlike Ethereum—where each smart contract is an account with the execution logic and storage tied together—Solana’s smart contracts are entirely stateless. State must be passed to accounts for them to execute on.</p><p>Let’s look at a code example. In the Solidity code below, state is tied to the smart contract with the line <code>int private count = 0.</code></p>"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-d6bc7586e8784faf97b1647b2af7c298",
            "component": {
              "name": "Code Block",
              "options": {
                "code": "contract Counter {\n  int private count = 0;\n  function incrementCounter() public\n    { count += 1;\n    }\n  function getCount() public constant returns (int) {\n    return count;\n  }\n}",
                "language": "solidity"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-1a50eb376c644a09ac4a3e9938edfc08",
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<p>\n  With Rust (Solana) there is a struct within the smart contract stating\n  initialize_counter. This initial counter creates an account with a count of 0.\n  The account is passed to this counter to increment the count. This keeps state\n  from being kept within the smart contract itself.\n</p>\n"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-e762e141a954453186cb061414ac1154",
            "component": {
              "name": "Code Block",
              "options": {
                "code": "#[program]\npub mod counter_anchor {\n  use super::*;\n\n  pub fn initialize_counter(_ctx: Context<InitializeCounter>) -> Result<()> {\n    Ok(())\n  }\n\n  pub fn increment(ctx: Context<Increment>) -> Result<()> {\n  ctx.accounts.counter.count = ctx.accounts.counter.count.checked_add(1).unwrap();\n    Ok(())\n  }\n}\n\n#[derive(Accounts)]\npub struct InitializeCounter<'info> {\n  #[account(mut)]\n  pub payer: Signer<'info>,\n  #[account(\n    init,\n    space = 8 + Counter::INIT_SPACE,\n    payer = payer\n    )]\n  pub counter: Account<'info, Counter>,\n  pub system_program: Program<'info, System>,\n}\n\n#[derive(Accounts)]\npub struct Increment<'info> {\n  #[account(mut)]\n  pub counter: Account<'info, Counter>,\n}\n\n#[account]\n#[derive(InitSpace)]\npub struct Counter {\n  count: u64,\n}\n",
                "language": "rust"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-947801ab073a4a6a9f70452a44629ed4",
            "component": {
              "name": "Copy",
              "options": {
                "rawHtml": "<p>With Solana, data is stored in separate accounts outside of the program. To execute the logic in a program, pass the account to be performed on.&nbsp;</p><p>In the case of this counter program, pass a counter account to the program when calling the increment function, and the program then increments the value in the counter account.</p><h3>Benefits of the Account Model Design</h3><p>One of the primary benefits of this account model is program reusability.&nbsp;</p><p>With the ERC20 interface on Ethereum, every time a developer creates a new token, they must redeploy the ERC20 smart contract to Ethereum with its specified values. This redeployment incurs a high cost.</p><p>But with Solana, it’s not necessary to create and deploy a new smart contract in order to create a new token. Instead, create a new account, known as the mint account, using the <a href=\"https://spl.solana.com/token\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Solana Token Program</a>, passing details such as number of tokens, decimal points, who can mint, and more.</p><p>And this can be done by simply sending a transaction to the Token Program. Using the Solana Program Library CLI, for example, it’s just a single command:</p>"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
                "boxSizing": "border-box"
              }
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "@builder.io/sdk:Element",
            "@version": 2,
            "id": "builder-44932d947c944b259f331426b95706b5",
            "component": {
              "name": "Code Block",
              "options": {
                "code": "$ spl-token create-token",
                "language": "rust"
              }
            },
            "responsiveStyles": {
              "large": {
                "display": "flex",
                "flexDirection": "column",
                "position": "relative",
                "flexShrink": "0",
